The African wind, the Greek name for which is Libs‚ will blow from the south-west, directly opposite to Aquilo; when animals after coupling turn towards this quarter, you may be sure that they have got females.

The third⁰ line from the north, which we have drawn transversely to the shadow and have called the decuman, will have the sunrise at the equinoxcs and the Subsolanus wind, called by the Greeks AphelioteS. This is the proper aspect for farm-houses and vinc- yards in healthy localities. This wind itself brings gentle rains; still Favonius, the wind in the opposite quarter, blowing from the equinoctial sunset‚ the Greek name for which is ZephyruS, is gentler and drier. This is the direction in which Cato recom- mended that olive-yards should face3 this wind inaugurates the spring, and opens up the land, having a healthy touch of cold, and it will give the right time for pruning vines, tending crops, planting trees, grafting fruit-trees and treating olives; and its breeze will have a nutritive effect. The fourth line from the north, lying nearest the south on the eastern side, will have the sunrise at midwintcr and the wind Volturnus, the Greek name for which is Eurus, which itself also is rather dry and warm3 this is the proper aspect for beehives and for vineyards in Italy, and the provinces of Gaul.
